Interviewer [I]: Now I am talking with Priya, a second year electrical engineering student. Priya has just tried out our product, the minimum viable product. First question, after getting used to this product, what do you think it is trying to help you with?
Priya [P]: From what I can see, it's basically a one stop shop for figuring out your degree at UQ. Instead of bouncing between the programs and courses website and your student centre, it pulls everything together. Course info, prerequisites, degree planning, all in one place. It seems especially useful for mapping out which courses feed into each other.
[I]: So how useful does the idea of seeing a full course plan based on your degree feel to you?
[P]: Very useful, honestly. Engineering degrees are notoriously rigid with sequencing. if you miss one course, it can push back your entire graduation timeline. Having a visual layout of all four or five years would save a lot of stress. Right now I literally have a spreadsheet I built myself to track what leads to what, so seeing that built into a platform is a relief.
[I]: How valuable is it to know what future courses depend on a course as a prerequisite?
[P]: Extremely valuable for engineering specifically. Some of our courses are only offered once a year, so if you drop one without realising it unlocks three others down the line, you can end up stuck for a whole semester. The tree visualisation is a great idea. It makes the domino effect of course choices really obvious at a glance.
[I]: Let's talk about the rating and review feature. The reviews are scripted for now, but how helpful do you think real student reviews would be for choosing your courses?
[P]: For engineering, this would be massive. Some courses have a reputation for brutal exams or really poor lecture recordings, but you only find that out by asking a senior student or stumbling onto a Reddit thread. Having that consolidated on the same platform where I'm already planning my semester would make the whole process so much smarter.
[I]: Is there any information you would expect to see that is missing from the demo?
[P]: A few things. The workload per course would be really helpful — not just the unit count but like, estimated hours per week. For engineering that varies wildly between courses. Also contact hours, whether a course is heavily lab based or lecture based matters a lot for timetable clashes. And semester availability is a must, I didn't see that anywhere.
[I]: Would this reduce the need to check multiple websites when choosing courses? Why or why not?
[P]: Largely yes. My current process involves the UQ course page, the faculty handbook PDF, my SI net enrolment, and usually a Teams message to an older student. If this platform had real data and real reviews, it would cut at least three of those steps out. The degree plan page especially. Seeing the recommended semester sequence with clickable courses is exactly what I've been wishing existed.
[I]: How would you feel about advertisements being shown while using a product like this?
[P]: I wouldn't mind static ads as long as they're not in the way of the actual content. Engineering students are constantly looking for internships and part time tutoring, so ads targeted toward that demographic would actually be useful rather than annoying. Just please no pop ups, if I'm mid planning and a full screen ad fires, I'm closing the tab immediately.
[I]: Thank you, that's all for the interview. Nice to meet you.
[P]: You too, thanks for having me.
